XVA Workbook¶

--- Nov-26-2019, Alan, Shaolun.du@gmail.com

This is a detailed documentation on XVA calculation (CVA/DVA) with QuantLib implementation. This workbook is heavily depeneded on previous posts such as bootstrapping, swap valuaiton and short rate model. If you do not familier with those terms and methods PLEASE refer to my previous posts. Execpt for CVA and DVA there are lots of xVAs such as FVA(Funding Valuation Adjustment), KVA(the Valuation Adjustment for regulatory capital through the life of the contract) and MVA(Margin Valuation Adjustment). I will only go over CVA/DVA in this notebook.

Since financial crisis 2008, investors pays more and more attention on credit risks and the CVA evolvs into a bigger topic in pricing adjustments. Bascially, an X-Value Adjustment (XVA) is a generic term referring collectively to a number of different Valuation Adjustments in relation to derivative instruments held by banks. The purpose of these is twofold: primarily to hedge for possible losses due to counterparty default; but also, to determine (and hedge) the amount of capital required under Basel III. For a discussion as to the impact of xVA on the bank's overall balance sheet, return on equity, and dividend policy, see: XVA has, in many institutions, led to the creation of specialized desks. Note that the various XVA require careful and correct aggregation without double counting.

There are three methods for CVA/DVA calculations:

  • Simple method: The simple method use counterparty default spread(CDS) adjusted discounting curve to do double curve valuation. Compared to original OIS or LIBOR curve discounting results. The difference is CVA.
  • Swaption heding method: this method involves using swaption as the potential hedging costs for a given swap. If investor can hege their potential exposure completely then the hedging cost will be its CVA. In this method, as the swap life shorten, it will be hedged with a shorter swaption so we need the actual volatility surface as well as curve data for swaption valuation.
  • Simulation method: This is the method I will go over in this notebook, because it requires a pretty complex programming ability I will do it in servel steps. Basically, this calculation involves risk factor modeling to get a short rate engine for potential interests path and swap valuation engine to re-value swap on each rate path and default curve modeling. In the end, we will take convolution of CDS curve and the average of positive value to get CVA and negative value to get DVA.

To start, please import the library:

NOTE: I will use USD curve as an example going forward, and I will talk about how to get other major currency curves as variantion to USD curves in the end. For XCS pricing, I will use USD/EUR cross currency swap as example. And I will continue to use the valibrated short rate HW model in the previous post.

def Bootstrapping( Market, Convention ):
    sDate = Market["SDate"]
    ql.Settings.instance().evaluationDate = sDate
    # Convert market quotes into QuantLib "Quote objects"
    deposits = Market["Cash"]
    futures  = Market["Future"]
    swaps    = Market["Swap"]
    deposits_con  = Convention["Cash"]
    futuresc_con  = Convention["Future"]
    swaps_con     = Convention["Swap"]
    for n,unit in deposits.keys():
        deposits[(n,unit)] = ql.SimpleQuote(deposits[(n,unit)])
    for d in futures.keys():
        futures[d] = ql.SimpleQuote(futures[d])
    for n,unit in swaps.keys():
        swaps[(n,unit)] = ql.SimpleQuote(swaps[(n,unit)])
    # Build up helpers for curve building
    depositHelpers = [ ql.DepositRateHelper( ql.QuoteHandle(deposits[(n,unit)]),
                                             ql.Period(n,unit), deposits_con["SettlementDays"],
                                             deposits_con["Calendar"], deposits_con["BsDay"],
                                             deposits_con["EOM"], deposits_con["DayCount"])
                       for n, unit in deposits.keys() ]
    futuresHelpers = [ ql.FuturesRateHelper( ql.QuoteHandle(futures[d]),
                                             d, futuresc_con["LengthInMonths"],
                                             futuresc_con["Calendar"], futuresc_con["BsDay"],
                                             futuresc_con["EOM"], futuresc_con["DayCount"],
                                             futuresc_con["ConVes_Adj"])
                       for d in futures.keys() ]
    swapHelpers = [ ql.SwapRateHelper( ql.QuoteHandle(swaps[(n,unit)]),
                                       ql.Period(n,unit), swaps_con["Calendar"],
                                       swaps_con["FixedLegFrequency"], swaps_con["FixedLegAdjustment"],
                                       swaps_con["FixedLegDayCounter"], swaps_con["Index"])
                    for n, unit in swaps.keys() ]
    # term-structure construction
    helpers = depositHelpers + futuresHelpers + swapHelpers # Helpers combined
    yts = ql.PiecewiseFlatForward( sDate, helpers, ql.Actual360()) # Forward curve defination
    yts.enableExtrapolation()
    return yts
# Generate USE LIBOR yield curve with TermStructure object
base_yts = Bootstrapping(Mkt_dict, Con_dict)
hyts = ql.RelinkableYieldTermStructureHandle(base_yts) # Build discounting curve into a term structure

NOTE: here, the termstructure is defined based on period, meaning it is shifted date on current date. If we changed the evaluation date the whole termstructure will be bring forward. This is pretty stupid when we are running potential exposures.

In [3]:
# helper function for rate path generation
def generate_curves( t_date, i_seq, 
                     num_paths, timestep):
    # generate a set of curves objects
    curves = []
    tt_pp = i_seq.next().value()
    time = [t_date+ int(tt_pp.time(j)*360) for j in range(len(tt_pp))]
    for i in range(num_paths):
        sample_path = i_seq.next()
        path = sample_path.value()
        value = [path[j] for j in range(len(path))]
        curves.append(ql.ZeroCurve(time, value, ql.Thirty360()))
    return curves

In [36]:
# Running different curves with fined timegrids
Max_Year = 10
timegrid = [ todays_date + ql.Period(i*2, ql.Months) for i in range(6*Max_Year) ]
# Adding fixing date from floating sechdule
timegrid += [LiborXm.fixingDate(x) for x in V_Swap_Dict["Float_Leg"]["floatSchedule"]]
timegrid = np.sort(np.unique(timegrid))
values_board = np.zeros((len(curves),len(timegrid))) # Matrix for swap values(NOT NPV)
npv_board = np.zeros((len(curves),len(timegrid)))
ql.IndexManager.instance().clearHistories()
#LiborXm = ql.USDLibor(ql.Period(3, ql.Months),hyts)
for loc_c in range(0, len(curves)):
    # !!!Pay sepcial attention here:
    # we are rebuilding zero rates curve into discounting curve.
    dis_facs = [curves[loc_c].discount(ttt) for ttt in timegrid]
    ycd = ql.DiscountCurve(timegrid,dis_facs,ql.Thirty360())
    ycd.enableExtrapolation()
    hyts.linkTo(ycd)
    for t in range(0, len(timegrid)):
        # Do valuation on timegrid
        p_date = timegrid[t]
        ql.Settings.instance().setEvaluationDate(p_date)
        if LiborXm.isValidFixingDate(p_date):
            fixing = LiborXm.fixing(p_date)
            LiborXm.addFixing(p_date, fixing)
        values_board[loc_c][t] = swap_test.NPV() # get swap value in futures
        npv_board[loc_c][t] = values_board[loc_c][t]*curves[loc_c].discount(p_date) # value times discount factor

Step 3 - Potential Exposure & Default Curve:¶

After we generate future value path, the next step is to calculate the convolution of positive/negative potential exposure with default probability curve. I will go over them seperately in the following. We also will assume a flat default risk curve(can be changed with user specific needs) and calculate default rate using the same time grid in the potential exposure generatation.

NOTE: For CVA calculation we use positive pontential exposure and for DVA use negative potential exposure.

The following code is used to calculate potential exposure:

CVA(DVA) is the convolution of average potential positive(negative) value path with default probability for each piece.

In [55]:
# Calculation of the default probs
defaultProb_vec = np.vectorize(pd_curve.defaultProbability)
dPD = defaultProb_vec(timegrid[:-1], timegrid[1:])
# Calculation of the CVA
recovery = 0.4
CVA = (1-recovery) * np.sum(EdE[1:] * dPD)
print(CVA)

Summary¶

In the above notebook, I detailed how to calculate CVA/DVA for a single swap under a live market condition. This monte-carlo simulation frame work is strong and helpful when we are doing risk calculations. In this notebook, we used bootstrapping method, swap pricing method, short rate model calibration method and default probability model to get eventually a single number CVA/DVA. The key point is to generate a list of values under different possible market conditions. Please pay attention to the following key points:

  • Short rate model calibration, we are using Hull-White model and calibrate it towards market ATM swaption volatility surface. The reason behind this comes from we are trying to price a swap CVA/DVA if in the future, one wants to deal with different market instrument, then you should calibrate the model to different market volatility data.

  • One more thing about the calibration, inorder to price the CVA/DVA correctly, we need to keep the short rate model calibration closer to market instruments. Meaning if the swap we want to price has 7 year maturity, then we need to get market ATM volatility data diagonally with 1Y6Y, 2Y5Y, 3Y4Y, 4Y3Y, 5Y2Y, 6Y1Y.

  • For exposure calculation, we need to rebuild the simulation path into discounting curve, please refer to corresponding code block. The reason for this is the swap engine takes only discounting factors (See swap_engine = ql.DiscountingSwapEngine(hyts)).

  • The default curve we are using here is a flat default curve which can be changed with different default rate to different time period. </span> In the next post, I will use a simliar method to calcuate VaR values with Monte-Carlo simulation in interests rate area.

Summary QA:

  • Why we need to transfer zero curve in discounting curve? A: Because we are using discounting swap pricing engine, we need feed the engine with a discounting curve. You do not need to transfer the zero curve in to discounting curve if you already have a discouting curve. For example, change the code "zeros_r = [hyts.zeroRate(d, ql.Thirty360(), ql.Continuous).rate() for d in sample_dates]" into something like "zeros_r = [hyts.zeroRate(d, ql.Thirty360(), ql.Continuous).discount() for d in sample_dates]" also works. What we did in the example is to show the reader a plot with potential rate path.

  • Why the future exposure path has steeled value? A: This is a common mistake when we deal with Monte-Carlo, since QuantLib has its own implementation of pricing date and fixing control. Please pay attention to the valuation matrix generation block. Basically, we need to reset valuaiton date and clear all fixing dates before running different curves.
